<item>
            <title>[THRIFT-2375] Excessive &lt;br&gt;&apos;s in generated HTML</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/THRIFT-2375</link>
                <project id="12310800" key="THRIFT">Thrift</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;This was working &quot;right&quot; (at least how I thought it should work) back in 0.9.0 going back at least to 0.7.0 and introduced in 0.9.1 &lt;br/&gt;
&lt;a href=&quot;https://git-wip-us.apache.org/repos/asf?p=thrift.git;a=commit;h=63e3c63&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://git-wip-us.apache.org/repos/asf?p=thrift.git;a=commit;h=63e3c63&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The issue is that there is a &apos;&amp;lt;br&amp;gt;&apos; in HTML after every newline in the source comment (thrift).   I assume that this was not the intention of the &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/THRIFT-1800&quot; title=&quot;Documentation text not always escaped correctly when rendered to HTML&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;THRIFT-1800&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;THRIFT-1800&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt; change.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I will attach complete sample thrift files and html output, but here is a summary:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This is what the output USED to look like&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;lt;tr&amp;gt;&amp;lt;td&amp;gt;1&amp;lt;/td&amp;gt;&amp;lt;td&amp;gt;theThing&amp;lt;/td&amp;gt;&amp;lt;td&amp;gt;&amp;lt;code&amp;gt;i32&amp;lt;/code&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/td&amp;gt;&amp;lt;td&amp;gt;Some comments can go for quite a while and may span multiple&lt;br/&gt;
lines.  What looks like a good spot to break a line in the&lt;br/&gt;
thrift file may turn out to be not so great in HTML.  In&lt;br/&gt;
fact in HTML we should let the browser decide when to start&lt;br/&gt;
a new lines.  Users can still&lt;br/&gt;
insert a break&amp;lt;br&amp;gt; when they really need/want it&lt;br/&gt;
&amp;lt;/td&amp;gt;&amp;lt;td&amp;gt;required&amp;lt;/td&amp;gt;&amp;lt;td&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/td&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/tr&amp;gt;&lt;br/&gt;
&amp;lt;/table&amp;gt;&amp;lt;br/&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/div&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/div&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/body&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/html&amp;gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;And this is what it looks like today&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;lt;tr&amp;gt;&amp;lt;td&amp;gt;1&amp;lt;/td&amp;gt;&amp;lt;td&amp;gt;theThing&amp;lt;/td&amp;gt;&amp;lt;td&amp;gt;&amp;lt;code&amp;gt;i32&amp;lt;/code&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/td&amp;gt;&amp;lt;td&amp;gt;Some comments can go for quite a while and may span multiple&amp;lt;br/&amp;gt;lines.  What looks like a good spot to break a li&lt;br/&gt;
ne in the&amp;lt;br/&amp;gt;thrift file may turn out to be not so great in HTML.  In&amp;lt;br/&amp;gt;fact in HTML we should let the browser decide when to start&amp;lt;br/&amp;gt;a new lines.  Users can still&amp;lt;br/&amp;gt;&lt;br/&gt;
insert a break&amp;lt;br&amp;gt; when they really need/want it&amp;lt;br/&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/td&amp;gt;&amp;lt;td&amp;gt;required&amp;lt;/td&amp;gt;&amp;lt;td&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/td&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/tr&amp;gt;&lt;br/&gt;
&amp;lt;/table&amp;gt;&amp;lt;br/&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/div&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/div&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/body&amp;gt;&amp;lt;/html&amp;gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;

</description>
